# 🔹 Universal Turing Machine (UTM)

A **Universal Turing Machine (UTM)** is a TM that can simulate **any other Turing Machine**.

It takes as input:

* The description of another TM.
* The input string for that TM.

📌 **Modern computers are conceptually similar to Universal Turing Machines.**

---

# 🔹 Church–Turing Thesis

The **Church–Turing Thesis** states:

> Any computation that can be performed by an algorithm can be performed by a Turing Machine.

Important:

* It is **not a mathematical theorem**.
* It is a widely accepted foundational principle in computer science.

---

# 🔹 Multi-Tape Turing Machine

A Multi-Tape TM has:

* Multiple tapes
* Multiple heads

Advantages:

* Simpler algorithms
* Faster execution

📌 **Recognition power is the same as a single-tape TM.** Multi-tape TMs are more efficient but **not more powerful**.

---

# 🔹 TM vs PDA vs DFA

| Feature   | DFA     | PDA             | TM                     |
| --------- | ------- | --------------- | ---------------------- |
| Memory    | None    | Stack           | Infinite Tape          |
| Read      | Yes     | Yes             | Yes                    |
| Write     | No      | Limited (Stack) | Yes                    |
| Move Left | No      | No              | Yes                    |
| Languages | Regular | Context-Free    | Recursively Enumerable |

---

# 🔹 Applications of Turing Machines

* Formal computation models
* Complexity theory
* Artificial Intelligence (theoretical foundations)
* Compiler design concepts
* Algorithm analysis
* Decidability and computability

